  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including China, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves a series of transactions or steps that obscure the origin of the funds, making it difficult for authorities to trace them back to their illegal source.\n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **\"Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China\"**, which was enacted in 2006 and has been amended to strengthen its provisions. The law imposes obligations on financial institutions to establish anti-money laundering (AML) systems, conduct customer due diligence, and report suspicious transactions to authorities. Additionally, individuals or entities found guilty of money laundering can face severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment.\n\nChina actively participates in international efforts to combat money laundering through its membership in organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for AML and counter-terrorism financing (CFT). By aligning with international standards, China demonstrates its commitment to combating this illegal activity and maintaining the integrity of its financial system.",
